    <!-- Title block -->
    <header class="mb-8">
      <p class="text-xs font-medium uppercase tracking-wide text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400">State Board Prep</p>
      <h1 class="mt-2 text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        What to Expect on Your Barber State Board Exam
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-300 max-w-2xl">
        This is the walk-through nobody gives you: how the day flows, what they actually watch for,
        and what you need to bring so you’re not that person getting turned away at check-in.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400">
        Last updated: <span id="updatedDate">2025</span> • Estimated read time: 7–10 minutes
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- Two-column layout (content + outline) -->
    <div class="grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[minmax(0,1.8fr)_minmax(0,1fr)]">
      <!-- MAIN ARTICLE -->
      <article class="prose prose-zinc max-w-none dark:prose-invert prose-sm sm:prose-base">
        <!-- Intro -->
        <section id="overview">
          <h2>Big picture: how the day works</h2>
          <p>
            Every state does the details a little different, but the basic pattern is the same:
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li>Arrive early, check in, show ID and admission letter.</li>
            <li>Locker or station assignment, kit check, quick instructions.</li>
            <li>Written exam (computer based) and/or practical exam on a set schedule.</li>
            <li>Proctors score your practical while you clean up and sign out.</li>
            <li>Results are posted or emailed by the testing agency or your state board.</li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            The exam is not about “perfect fades.” It’s about: sanitation, following directions,
            and staying in control when you’re being watched.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- What to bring -->
        <section id="what-to-bring">
          <h2>What you need to bring</h2>
          <p>Always check the official candidate bulletin for your state. As a baseline, plan on:</p>
          <h3>Required at check-in</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Government-issued photo ID (name must match your exam registration).</li>
            <li>Admission letter / email printout from the testing company.</li>
            <li>Any state-specific forms they tell you to bring.</li>
          </ul>
          <h3>Your practical kit</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>
              Clean, labeled kit with <strong>disinfected tools</strong> in closed containers
              and visibly separated “clean” vs “used.”
            </li>
            <li>
              Mannequin(s) with appropriate hair length for the required services
              (some states allow live models – follow your bulletin).
            </li>
            <li>EPA-registered disinfectant, barbacide jar or equivalent, spray bottles.</li>
            <li>Gloves, neck strips, capes, towels, drapes, razor with guard / blades as required.</li>
            <li>Trash bags and “soiled linens” bag clearly marked.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-xs text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400">
            Pro tip: pack your kit in “exam order.” First task on top, last task at the bottom,
            so you’re not digging around with the clock running.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- Written exam -->
        <section id="written">
          <h2>The written exam: what it really feels like</h2>
          <p>
            The written (theory) exam is usually on a computer in a quiet room with other trades
            testing at the same time. Expect:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Multiple choice questions only.</li>
            <li>Time limit between 90–120 minutes depending on state.</li>
            <li>No phones, notes, or smart watches. Lockers or plastic bags for personal items.</li>
          </ul>
          <h3>Question types you’ll see</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Sanitation, disinfection, blood exposure procedures.</li>
            <li>Basic anatomy, hair and skin structure.</li>
            <li>Chemical services, perms/relaxers (even if you’re not hyped about them).</li>
            <li>Clipper cutting theory, elevations, guideline language.</li>
            <li>State law: hours, fines, license rules, renewal.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Don’t overcomplicate it. You’re not writing essays. You’re picking the safest, most
            “by the book” option every time.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- Practical exam -->
        <section id="practical">
          <h2>The practical exam: step-by-step flow</h2>
          <p>
            The practical is where most people get in their head. The proctors aren’t there to
            destroy you. They’re there to see if you can work clean, organized, and safe.
          </p>
          <h3>Typical sequence (varies by state)</h3>
          <ol>
            <li>Set up your station, sanitize hands, prepare your mannequin.</li>
            <li>Haircut service (usually a tapered cut with outlined perimeter).</li>
            <li>Shaving or facial service (razor handling and safety).</li>
            <li>Sanitation and cleanup procedure.</li>
          </ol>
          <h3>What proctors are actually watching</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Did you sanitize before you touch anything?</li>
            <li>Are clean and dirty tools clearly separated and labeled?</li>
            <li>Do you drape correctly and protect the client’s skin/clothes?</li>
            <li>Are you controlling the razor and clippers safely around skin and ears?</li>
            <li>Do you follow directions in order without skipping steps?</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            They’re not grading you on IG-level blends. They’re grading you on
            “would I trust this person with the public’s health and safety?”
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- Day-of timeline -->
        <section id="timeline">
          <h2>Sample day-of timeline</h2>
          <p>Adjust times to whatever your admission letter says, but here’s a realistic flow:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>7:30–8:00 AM</strong> – Arrive, park, bathroom, calm down.</li>
            <li><strong>8:00–8:20 AM</strong> – Check-in, ID check, locker assignment.</li>
            <li><strong>8:30–10:00 AM</strong> – Written exam window.</li>
            <li><strong>10:15–11:00 AM</strong> – Practical room setup + instructions.</li>
            <li><strong>11:00–12:30 PM</strong> – Practical exam services.</li>
            <li><strong>12:30–1:00 PM</strong> – Cleanup, sign out, results instructions.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- Scoring / results -->
        <section id="scoring">
          <h2>Scoring and what happens if you don’t pass</h2>
          <p>
            Most testing companies give you a score report with each domain broken down:
            sanitation, haircutting, shaving, etc. This is your roadmap for what to fix.
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Keep your score sheet. It tells you exactly where you got hit.</li>
            <li>In a lot of states you can retake just the section you failed (written or practical).</li>
            <li>Use the waiting period to drill your weak areas instead of restarting from scratch.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- Quick checklist -->
        <section id="checklist">
          <h2>Night-before checklist</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Kit packed and labeled in exam order.</li>
            <li>ID + admission letter in your bag.</li>
            <li>Clothes picked out (comfortable, professional, closed-toe shoes).</li>
            <li>Alarms set with travel time and traffic in mind.</li>
            <li>Snacks and water ready for after the exam.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Last thing: sleep. Showing up tired and anxious is how people forget simple steps
            like sanitizing or draping and lose points they didn’t need to lose.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- CTA -->
        <section id="next-steps">
          <h2>Next steps</h2>
          <p>
            Use this page as your “big picture” guide. Your next move is to drill details:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Run through your state’s official candidate bulletin line by line.</li>
            <li>Practice full exam run-throughs with a timer and your kit.</li>
            <li>Use the FadeJunkie test prep tools to lock in theory questions.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            When this doesn’t feel mysterious any more, you stop wasting energy on panic
            and can focus on just executing.
          </p>
        </section>
      </article>

      <!-- SIDEBAR / OUTLINE -->
